6","1258":"1258","about 1239":"circa 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","about 1220":"circa 1220","Aft 1292":"na 1292","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1220–Aft 1292":"about 1220–after 1292","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1220–1292":"1220–1292","1224–Female":"1224–Deceased","1240–1336":"1240–1336","1245–1300":"1245–1300","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","Aft 1248":"after 1248","11 January 1240":"11 January 1240","1220":"1220","ABT 1214":"about 1214","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","1292":"1292","1248":"1248","1336":"1336","1258":"1258","about 1239":"about 1239","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","about 1220":"about 1220","Aft 1292":"after 1292","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom",",,, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mautby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places called Maltby (South Yorkshire, Lincolnshire) or Maltby le Marsh (Lincolnshire); possibly occasionally from Maltby (North Yorkshire) or Mautby (Norfolk). The placenames derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Malti</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Maltbie","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Maltby  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Mautby was born about 1220, in Paston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walter de Mauteby, was 49 and his mother, Christian Bassingham, was 50. He married Isabel Flegg about 1239, in Paston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died after 1292."},"et":{"about 1220–Aft 1292":"umbes 1220–pärast 1292","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1220–1292":"1220–1292","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1240–1336":"1240–1336","1245–1300":"1245–1300","1172–1248":"1172–1248","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","Aft 1248":"pärast 1248","11 January 1240":"11. jaanuar 1240","1220":"1220","ABT 1214":"umbes 1214","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1172":"1172",